Saudi was really one of the safest countries I visited, in my entire 18 years of being there I have not experienced a single crime! nor have I ever felt unsafe. It is the kind of country where you can leave your car running in the winter to warm up while having breakfast at home without worrying about anyone stealing your car. I could leave my phone and wallet in resturants to go wash my hands with out having to worry about them going missing.

I really miss it, I made some great friends there, both Saudi and non Saudi. I would like to visit it after all these corona lock down is over.

I lived there 1994-99 at KFUPM Dhahran. If you get the chance to visit the Iris Fields of Tumair north of Riyadh - go. They are old agricultural fields where grow iris in huge drifts which with the right rains all bloom in one hour on (I think 20 March or thereabouts). It is spectacular to see only green then on one hour the whole field is in bloom purple. Additionally visit Thumamah where you can see the valley Wadi Howtat Bani Tamiim where gazelles and ibex roam in a huge reserve.
Wish you have a good and safe journey where ever you go! Ameen.

To answer your question, there used to be strict laws for that stuff a while ago, they slowly relaxed laws to allow women not to cover their hair years ago. Some years after that, women just had to wear their abaya over themselves, but could have it open. Last year the abaya as a whole was no longer required. I was actually in Riyadh a month ago and most people still cover, but i saw for example a saudi woman pianist dressed in a suite playing piano in public, with a short cut hair. There were a number of locals and non-locals who didn’t cover or wear an abaya, but doing so is a symbol of respect and modesty, so it’s still a very common thing. You can wear what you want there, just not revealing, tight clothing or shorts
